file=Brand Studio/weave/custom/brand-story-arcs/assets/story-arc-template.md · [ns:[Brand Name] Story Arc — TEMPLATE=> **This is a template, not a story.** Fill it with the operator from the business's REAL\n> history, customers, and market — nothing invented, no manufactured stakes, no fictional\n> origin. Saved at weave's config `story_arc_path`, one per brand. Versioned and\n> operator-owned: weave proposes amendments, only the operator adopts them.\n> The test of a finished arc: every future campaign can be positioned as a chapter of it,\n> and no competitor could claim this arc with the logo swapped.\n\n**Brand:** [name] \· **Arc version:** [v1.0] \· **Date:** [YYYY-MM-DD]\n**Built from:** [founder interview / company history / customer conversations — name the real sources]\n**Amendment rule:** [how the arc changes: proposed by weave or operator, adopted by operator,\nversion bump + one-line rationale, logged in the chapter registry. Retcons are prohibited;\nnew acts are how arcs grow.]\n\n · 1tw:1. The World's Change (why this story is happening now)=[One paragraph. What shifted in the world — technology, behavior, market, rules — that made\nthe old way stop working and this brand possible. This is the story's engine: without a real\nchange, there's no movement to lead, only a product to sell.\nTest: is this change observably true, and would the audience nod at it?]\n · 2to:2. The Old Game and Its Villain (world-that-is)=- **The old way:** [how people solve this problem today — named plainly]\n- **The villain:** [NOT a competitor — the systemic enemy: the wasted hours, the middleman markup,\nthe one-size-fits-nobody assumption, the paperwork. Specific enough to be attacked in chapters.]\n- **What it costs the hero:** [concrete, real costs — time, money, dignity, opportunity. Numbers\nand scenes beat adjectives.]\n · 3th:3. The Hero (the customer — never the brand)=- **Who they are:** [the specific person/business this story serves — from real customers]\n- **What they want:** [their goal in their words]\n- **Their struggle:** [what trying and failing under the old game actually looks like — real scenes]\n- **Guardrail:** every chapter casts them as Luke. The brand is Obi-Wan. A chapter where the\nbrand saves the day instead of equipping the hero is hero-syndrome → OFF-ARC.\n · 4tg:4. The Guide and the Tool (the brand's role)=- **Why this brand can guide:** [the earned credibility — the founder lived the problem /\nthe years in the trade / the insight nobody else had. REAL only.]\n- **The tool (lightsaber):** [what the brand puts in the hero's hands, stated as capability\nthe hero gains — not features the brand has]\n- **The five-second moment this brand sells:** [the singular moment of transformation a\ncustomer experiences — the moment 98% of every chapter exists to set up]\n · 5ts:5. The Stakes (the elephant)=[What is genuinely at risk if the hero stays in the old game — and it must be TRUE. Stakes\nappear early in every chapter; a story with nothing to lose is content.]\n · 6tp:6. The Promised Land (world-that-could-be)=- **The rallying cry:** [the object of the new game in one repeatable line — the phrase a\ncustomer could say at dinner of their own volition. Test: memorable, specific, theirs.]\n- **What the transformed world looks like:** [concrete scenes of life after — for the hero,\nnot the brand]\n · 7ta:7. The Acts (the arc's long shape)=[3–5 acts the story moves through over quarters/years — e.g., Act I: name the villain and\ngather the wronged \· Act II: arm the heroes, show the proof \· Act III: the new way becomes\nnormal. Each act has an exit condition. Campaigns are chapters WITHIN the current act.]\n · tb=\| Act \| The story's job in this act \| Exit condition \| Status \| · tb=\|---\|---\|---\|---\| · tb=\| I \| \| \| current/done/future \| · tb=\| II \| \| \| \| · 8cf:8. Canon Facts (the unbreakable list)=[The facts every chapter must respect — origin details, the named villain, load-bearing\nclaims, the rallying cry. Short list. Anything here changes only by amendment.]\n · 9c:9. Cross-References=- **Voice:** how this story is worded lives in lena's voice guide — arc constrains substance, voice constrains sound.\n- **Visuals:** atlas's kit; imagery direction should serve the acts (villain-era vs promised-land imagery differ).\n- **Investor narrative:** echo's pitch-narrative tells this same story to capital — facts identical, framing differs.\n- **Chapters told:** see the chapter registry (ledger) beside this file.\n